## Performance Metrics Explained

### Execution Time (ms)
- **What**: Total elapsed time from BeginMeasurement to EndMeasurement
- **Includes**: Algorithm execution + any Thread.Sleep() calls in slow mode
- **Precision**: Microseconds (via Stopwatch.GetTimestamp)
- **Unit**: Milliseconds

### CPU Percentage (%)
- **What**: CPU usage of the entire system during algorithm execution
- **Source**: Windows Performance Counter "% Processor Time" for _Total
- **Range**: 0-100% (may show 0 on systems without counter access)
- **Note**: Reflects **system-wide** CPU, not just the application

### Memory (MB)
- **What**: Net memory allocated/deallocated during algorithm execution
- **Method**: `GC.GetTotalMemory(false)` at start and end
- **Important**: Shows differential only, not total heap size
- **Unit**: Megabytes (automatically converted from bytes)

### Slow vs Fast Ratio
- **Formula**: `Average SLOW Time / Average FAST Time`
- **Interpretation**: 
  - Ratio of 15x = Slow-mode execution takes 15 times longer
  - Useful for quantifying the overhead of step-by-step visualization
  - Helps identify which algorithms benefit most from visual breakdown

### CPU Delta (?)
- **Formula**: `Average SLOW CPU% - Average FAST CPU%`
- **Interpretation**:
  - Positive delta = Slow mode consumes more CPU (expected due to refreshes)
  - Negative delta = Unusual, might indicate system variability
  - Larger delta = More UI overhead from animations

